29
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
OK, so first, let's talk about Swift multi-platform support,

30
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:38,000
its runtime and performance aspects that come with them.

31
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:40,000
Oh, I found it.

32
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:43,000
So, Swift has been growing into a language

33
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:48,000
with potential across many platforms.

34
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:51,000
Of course, it's a mainstream language

35
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:54,000
on upper platforms like iOS, watchOS,

36
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:59,000
visionOS, macOS, and tvOS.

37
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:02,000
It's also available on the other operating systems

38
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:04,000
like Windows and Linux,

39
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,000
and even supports web development paradigms

40
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:12,000
like the Wasm.

41
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,000
And experimentally,

42
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:17,000
it's also moving towards supporting embedded systems,

43
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:23,000
which are more minimum and have stricter environments.

44
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,000
Furthermore, an Android work group

45
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,000
has been launched in the Swift community,

46
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,000
and adoption for Android development

47
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:36,000
is also progressing.

48
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:37,000
As you can see,

49
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:40,000
the Swift supports a wide range of platforms

50
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,000
and continues to evolve.

51
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:43,000
When it comes to understanding

52
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,000
its multi-platform nature and its performance,

53
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,000
what we really need to look at

54
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:55,000
is how Swift works under the platform.

55
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:58,000
A Swift program doesn't run on its own.

56
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:03,000
It needs an environment that makes it behave as like Swift.

57
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:08,000
In other words, it's a runtime.

58
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:15,000
This runtime is called libswiftCcore on most platforms.

59
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:21,000
So,what exactly does libswiftCcore do?

60
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:25,000
As I mentioned earlier, libswiftCcore is a Swift runtime.

61
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:26,000
In other words,

62
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:32,000
it's a foundation that enables Swift to run on a platform.

63
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,000
libswiftCcore mainly exists

64
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:38,000
to support Swift dynamic features.

65
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:39,000
In construct,

66
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:41,000
the compiler handles the static side

67
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,000
like checking your code correctness,

68
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:50,000
performing optimization and building.

69
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:55,000
Therefore, the dynamic refers to things like reflecting memory layers,

70
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:56,000
performing allocations,

71
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:58,000
and managing memory

72
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:05,000
through the automatic reference counting.

73
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:08,000
The way libswiftCcore is distributed

74
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:14,000
varies by the platform.

75
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:15,000
On Apple platform,

76
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,000
it's bundled with the OS.

77
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:19,000
This is why some features

78
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:21,000
of newer Swift versions aren't available

79
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:26,000
until you update to the latest OS.

80
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:30,000
The benefit of having the OS provided

81
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:31,000
is that each application

82
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:34,000
doesn't need to include the runtime

83
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:40,000
and prevents upsides from growing.

84
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:41,000
For Linux programs,

85
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:43,000
you can choose to link the runtime statically

86
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:47,000
or include it as dynamic library.

87
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:49,000
Unlike on Apple platform,

88
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:51,000
without considering the OS version,

89
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:57,000
you can use the latest Swift features right away.

90
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:58,000
On Windows,

91
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:08,000
the current approach is to bundle it with the app as a dynamic library.

92
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
So on the OS environments we've talked about,

93
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:19,000
the runtime set up the Swift execution environment for us.

94
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:22,000
However, the runtime is by no means small

95
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:25,000
and in environments like embedded systems

96
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,000
where memory and storage are limited,

97
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:33,000
including if it's not practical.

98
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:35,000
So Swift allows you to build a program

99
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:37,000
for an embedded system

100
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:40,000
including a much smaller Swift environment.

101
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:46,000
This is called Embedded Swift.

102
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:49,000
Embedded Swift is an executables tailored

103
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:54,000
for an embedded environments.

104
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:58,000
By dropping some dynamic features to reduce binary size,

105
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,000
it delivers smaller Swift programs

106
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:04,000
suitable for embedded systems.

107
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:10,000
So how does the Embedded Swift stay small?

108
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:11,000
As you know,

109
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:13,000
Swift offers a wide range of features

110
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:20,000
and some of them are especially tied to runtime.

111
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:21,000
For example,

112
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:23,000
features like untyped throw, reflection,

113
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:26,000
any and weak require runtime metadata

114
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:28,000
and type information.

115
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:30,000
In embedded systems,

116
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:33,000
because environment is limited,

117
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:35,000
these features lead to runtime overhead

118
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:39,000
and increase your program size.

119
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:43,000
Embedded Swift provides a subset of Swift language

120
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:45,000
by removing such features

121
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:52,000
that would cause overhead in embedded systems.

122
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:55,000
Embedded Swift supports the standard library.

123
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:57,000
Features like codable, encodable,

124
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,000
and decodable aren't supported

125
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
because they require the reflection on runtime.

126
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:09,000
But most other familiar features are supported.

127
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:10,000
However, there are challenges

128
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:15,000
and one example is Array.

129
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:17,000
Swift Array is implemented

130
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,000
at dynamic heap allocated container

131
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:22,000
to provide rich functionality.

132
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,000
While it's safer to use than the C-style Array,

133
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:28,000
those rich features come with overhead.

134
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:34,000
Oh, I noticed that we have many Array talks today.

135
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:35,000
In embedded systems,

136
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:39,000
using Swift Array can be a costly choice

137
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:46,000
because that relies heavily on the heap.

138
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,000
So how can we overcome Array's costs

139
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:52,000
on embedded systems?

140
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
Starting with Swift 6.2,

141
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:58,000
InlineArray offers one way to address this challenge.

142
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Let's look at what makes Array costly

143
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:03,000
and how InlineArray solves it.

144
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:06,000
Also, we can see valuable hints

145
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:09,000
about what Swift performance really means

146
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:11,000
from Array challenges

147
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:14,000
and how it's solved by InlineArray.

148
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:23,000
So let's dive in and take a closer look together.

149
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:25,000
Now let's look at challenges of Array

150
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:29,000
and walk through how InlineArray works.

151
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:33,000
This is a kind of Array call you all write all the time.

152
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:36,000
Let's see how an Array is stored in memory

153
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:40,000
when this code is run.

154
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:43,000
First, since Array itself is a struct,

155
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
it starts in an area called stack.

156
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,000
You may already know about stack,

157
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:54,000
but let's take a moment to review what the stack is.

158
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
The stack is a memory-efficient region

159
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:58,000
used for storing local variables

160
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:03,000
and function calls.

161
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,000
Data gets allocated and freed

162
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:13,000
in a strict, last-in, first-out order.

163
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:15,000
I'll explain later, unlike the heap,

164
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:17,000
it doesn't need memory management

165
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:22,000
with reference count.

166
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:23,000
To give you a clear image,

167
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:26,000
let's look at what the stack actually is

168
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:30,000
and with example of a real function call.

169
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:32,000
First, let's see how the stack changes

170
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:37,000
when we call this test1 function.

171
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:39,000
When test1 function is called,

172
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:42,000
the stack gets a new block data on for it,

173
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:44,000
holding the test1 function information

174
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:48,000
like its local variable.

175
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:51,000
Then, after running some code inside test1,

176
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:56,000
as you can see, it's called test2.

177
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:01,000
At this point, what happens to the stack?

178
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:03,000
Well, just like before,

179
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:09,000
the information for test2 gets pushed on stack.

180
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:12,000
OK. Oh, sorry.

181
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:14,000
I didn't know my voice is small.

182
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:15,000
OK, sorry.

183
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:16,000
Just like before,

184
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:19,000
the information for test2 gets pushed on stack.

185
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:20,000
In this way,

186
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:27,000
each function data is managed on its stack frame.

187
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:29,000
When test2 finished

188
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:31,000
and execution returns to test1,

189
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:36,000
what happens to stack?

190
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:39,000
Since stack works in a last-in-first-out manner,

191
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:42,000
it popped out from top frame test2

192
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:44,000
and freed the block.

193
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:47,000
By releasing entire frame at once,

194
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:52,000
all of test2 data is cleared from memory.

195
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:53,000
When test1 finishes,

196
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:56,000
it's popped and freed in the same way.

197
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:57,000
It's clearly releasing all data

198
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:02,000
from the function code so far.

199
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:04,000
When you set block points in Xcode,

200
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:05,000
your app crashes.

201
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:08,000
You've probably seen this screen.

202
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:12,000
This list on the left is called call stack,

203
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:15,000
which is the same stack I'm talking about.

204
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:17,000
Each thread has its own stack,

205
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:19,000
and you can inspect detailed information

206
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:24,000
for each one right in Xcode.

207
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:26,000
Array also follows a similar flow

208
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:28,000
and is stored in stack,

209
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:31,000
but internal implementation uses the heap,

210
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:37,000
so things are not quite that straightforward.

211
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:40,000
To our flexible addition and removals,

212
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:42,000
an array maintains an internal buffer.

213
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:43,000
This buffer is stored

214
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:47,000
in the separate area from the stack frame.

215
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:51,000
That buffer is stored in the heap area.

216
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:53,000
Let's talk about heap.

217
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:54,000
It's a flexible memory area

218
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,000
used for long-lived or shared data

219
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:00,000
like class instances.

220
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:04,000
You can allocate a free memory in any order,

221
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:06,000
but that means system has to keep track

222
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:10,000
and manage it.

223
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:12,000
Also, allocating from the heap

224
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:14,000
is slower than using stack.

225
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:18,000
I'll describe later about it.

226
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:20,000
Let's also check how the heap works

227
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:22,000
using a simple example.

228
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:23,000
Here, as you can see,

229
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:25,000
we look at code that works

230
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:29,000
with an instance of some class type.

231
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:31,000
First, the reference address

232
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:35,000
to the class instance is stored in the stack.

233
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:37,000
Then, the class instance itself

234
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:39,000
is stored in the heap,

235
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:41,000
and the address on the stack

236
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:46,000
will point that heap location.

237
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:48,000
When your code takes or drops

238
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:49,000
a reference to the instance,

239
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:52,000
some count updates its internal written count.

240
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:56,000
This mechanism is called auto-reference counting.

241
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:57,000
That counter decides

242
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:59,000
whether the heap object should stay alive

243
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:05,000
or frees when it reaches zero.

244
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:07,000
When it reaches zero,

245
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:11,000
Swift frees the object memory on the heap.

246
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:16,000
That's how Swift manages memory in the heap.

247
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:18,000
Auto reference counting

248
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:20,000
actually comes with a hidden cost.

249
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:22,000
Like behind your Swift code,

250
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:25,000
the compiler inserts the extra instruction

251
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:27,000
to update the reference count.

252
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:30,000
This runs every time a reference changes

253
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:32,000
and over time.

254
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:38,000
That hidden work adds up to the performance cost.

255
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:40,000
Another thing to watch out for

256
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:43,000
with heap memory is fragmentation.

257
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:45,000
For example, let's imagine

258
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:50,000
we store some instance in the heap.

259
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:52,000
As your Swift code runs,

260
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,000
objects get freed and allocated,

261
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:00,000
leaving small gaps scattered throughout the heap.

262
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:01,000
This state,

263
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:04,000
and where small gaps are left scattered around,

264
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:08,000
is called fragmentation.

265
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:09,000
Now let's try creating

266
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:14,000
a larger class instance and putting it into the heap.

267
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:15,000
As you can see,

268
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:17,000
the heap has free space here and there,

269
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:19,000
but there isn't a spot large enough

270
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:22,000
for this large class instance.

271
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:24,000
The allocator may have to scan from the beginning

272
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:26,000
to find a big enough block

273
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:28,000
near to the end for a long time

274
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:31,000
or fail to find it.

275
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:33,000
In short, heap usage can incur the overhead

276
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:38,000
from fragmentation and such for continuous space.

277
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:39,000
So putting data on heap

278
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:42,000
can introduce various kinds of overhead.

279
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:44,000
In limited resource environment

280
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:45,000
like embedded system,

281
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:50,000
that impact becomes especially noticeable.

282
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:51,000
Let's also touch on the overhead

283
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:56,000
involved when working with regular array data.

284
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:58,000
For example, when you add an element to array,

285
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:02,000
there still is potential for overhead.

286
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:05,000
Because array is expected to modify,

287
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:07,000
its buffer is usually allocated

288
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:09,000
with some extra capacity

289
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:12,000
beyond the current number of elements.

290
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:15,000
But when that extra capacity runs out,

291
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:20,000
it allocates a new larger buffer.

292
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:24,000
Then all existing elements plus the new one

293
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:26,000
are copied into a new buffer

294
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:30,000
and referenced from the array struct.

295
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:32,000
The old buffer is then freed.

296
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:34,000
From performance perspective,

297
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:35,000
it's worth knowing that

298
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:37,000
this kind of copying and reallocation

299
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:41,000
can introduce overhead.

300
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:44,000
So here's a pitfall of array.

301
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:46,000
Even if it's just a small fixed array,

302
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:49,000
so it still puts it on a heap.

303
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:53,000
In environment with limited resources like embedded system,

304
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:56,000
that become a cost.

305
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:57,000
And if array grows,

306
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:00,000
you've got a buffer reallocation and copying.

307
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:06,000
So the question is how do we work on this?

308
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:10,000
Here, let's take a look at a good example

309
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:13,000
of old C array.

310
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:15,000
A C array is basically a fixed length array

311
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:18,000
stored on the stack.

312
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:21,000
Since embedded Swift can call into C,

313
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:23,000
so you could call C language

314
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:26,000
because that works a lot of main elements.

315
00:17:26,700 --> 00:17:32,266
But because it has no bond checks and cause unexpected behavior,

316
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:38,066
so ideally we just want to write it in Swift.

317
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:44,000
And that's a point of motivation

318
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:49,000
behind introducing InlineArray to Swift.

319
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:51,000
InlineArray will be stored stack

320
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:53,000
so we don't need to care overhead heap

321
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:58,000
for fixed size array.

322
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:00,000
InlineArray,in a way,

323
00:18:00,966 --> 00:18:03,900
Combines Swift safety with C array performance.

324
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:08,000
It's stored to stack with no heap allocation.

325
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:12,966
Its bond checks yet still highly performant.

326
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:18,000
InlineArray also has benefits in iOS development.

327
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:19,000
Even on iOS,

328
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:22,000
the stack advantage are significant.

329
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:26,000
It keeps data on the stack for low-latency access

330
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:30,000
and it eliminates heap allocation

331
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:35,000
overhead in performance-critical code.

332
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:37,700
Finally, let's take a look at what we learned today

333
00:18:37,700 --> 00:18:39,433
and think about what's important

334
00:18:39,433 --> 00:18:44,000
for understanding Swift evolution.

335
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:45,000
Swift is now designed

336
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:48,000
with much platform use in mind

337
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:49,000
and we discussed earlier

338
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:51,000
it also has growing focusing

339
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:56,000
on performance consensus features.

340
00:18:56,000 --> 00:18:58,000
To keep up with the Swift evolution

341
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:00,000
and truly understand it,

342
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:03,000
I believe these three things are key.

343
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:06,933
First, understand the motivation behind the evolution.

344
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:11,000
For example, code like the InlineArray we looked earlier

345
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:14,000
might not seem beneficial at first glance.

346
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:18,000
But every new feature comes with underlying motivation

347
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:21,000
or specific problems it aims to solve.

348
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:23,000
Without understanding these,

349
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:26,000
it's hard to see their value

350
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:28,000
or know when to use them.

351
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:31,000
By actively digging into proposals

352
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:33,000
for new Swift features,

353
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:35,000
you can uncover these motivations

354
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:37,000
and turn them into your tools

355
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:40,000
in your own power.

356
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:43,000
Next, understand Swift performance.

357
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:48,000
Swift offers many high-level conveniences,

358
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:53,000
but this sometimes hides costs under the hood.

359
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:55,000
So like heap allocation,

360
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:56,000
reference counting

361
00:19:56,000 --> 00:19:58,000
and buffer reallocation.

362
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:00,000
Knowing where these costs come from

363
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:04,000
and know how they differ across platforms

364
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:05,000
helps you write codes

365
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:10,000
that's both expressive and efficient.

366
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:14,000
Finally, understand the mechanism of your code.

367
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:17,000
Please look at your everyday code

368
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:19,000
through the lens of performance,

369
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:21,000
asking, is this the right tool?

370
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:23,000
Am I using it correctly?

371
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:26,000
And could it be improved?

372
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:31,000
It builds a deeper understanding of Swift.

373
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:33,000
Finally, I'd like to share a few more sessions

374
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:37,000
that can help deepen your understanding of Swift.

375
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:39,000
These talks and materials are great resources

376
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:42,000
for keeping up with Swift evolution

377
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
and strengthen your knowledge.

378
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:49,000
I encourage you to check them out.

379
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:50,000
Thank you for listening.

380
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:53,000
I hope this make your Swift journey great.

